{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"13a81567-c548-4fc9-a9e1-8b514b8734cd","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\nMSTest v4 changed the **test ID generation algorithm**. Azure DevOps matches tests by ID, so every test looks \"new.\" You can restore the v3 behavior in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\nor use the legacy strategy to preserve history continuity.\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's not associated with any specific test. Accessing `TestName` now throws. In v3 it returned the name of whichever test happened to trigger initialization (which was unreliable anyway).\n\nLet me fix your code:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01E3FFZWeReKVgyad53nGsqZ","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Fixing MSTest v4 issues"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_0127AnHbqLpT61YjNpu6Qrz4","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-f1d79f10744c454aa37acedfffb72274/SetupTests.cs","old_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        var testName = context.TestName;\n        // Log setup for specific test\n    }","new_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // In MSTest v4 the TestContext passed to [ClassInitialize] is class-scoped\n        // and has no test-specific properties. Use TestContext.FullyQualifiedTestClassName\n        // for class-level logging, or move per-test logic to [TestInitialize].\n        var className = context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName;\n        // Log setup for class\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-f1d79f10744c454aa37acedfffb72274/SetupTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"33c12b36-896f-4a35-a860-1cc69010391b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has upgraded to MSTest v4 and is experiencing specific issues. Let me address their questions based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 breaking changes.\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps** - This is a known MSTest v4 change. In v4, the default **test ID generation strategy changed**. MSTest v3 used a test ID based on the test method's fully qualified name, but v4 changed the algorithm, which means Azure DevOps sees them as completely different tests, losing history.\n\n2. **`TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`** - In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` methods is no longer associated with a specific test. Accessing `TestName` on it will throw because there's no test running yet at class initialization time. This is a behavioral change from v3 where it would return the name of the first test that triggered the class initialization.\n   \n3. **Other breaking changes to be aware of** - The unified `MSTest` package now replaces the separate framework, adapter, and analyzer packages. Properties like `TestName` and `FullyQualifiedTestClassName` may not be available in class or assembly initialization contexts. The test ID generation change also affects CI/CD history tracking, some analyzer rules are stricter, and there are changes to `DataRow` attributes and `DeploymentItem` behavior.\n\nNow I'll walk through how to address these migration issues and update the code accordingly.","outputTokens":916,"requestId":"5C20:3CEFF5:3FC53F:50D00D:69F56512"},"id":"d9b54923-050f-45fb-a580-016d6ce5346c","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:44:54.369Z","parentId":"b6a42968-26e0-467b-8044-87b560d9e8a4"}
